description: From Middle English dabben (“to strike”), probably of North Germanic origin, related to Old Icelandic dabba (“to tap, slap”), perhaps ultimately imitative. Compare also with Middle Dutch dabben (“to pinch, knead, fumble, dabble”) (Dutch dabben (“(of a horse) to stamp with the forelegs”)), Dutch deppen (“to dab”), possibly German tappen (“to fumble, grope”).
The noun is from Middle English dabbe (“a strike, blow”), from the verb. Related to tap. Compare also drub, dub.
African-American sense of “playful box” perhaps influenced by dap (“fistbump”).

entries.meaning: With a dab, or sudden contact.
A soft tap or blow; a blow or peck from a bird's beak; an aimed blow.
(African-American Vernacular) A soft, playful box given in greeting or approval.
examples: Coordinate terms: dap, fist bump, high five

definitionGroups.group: A small amount, a blob of some soft or wet substance.

entries.meaning: (slang) A small amount of hash oil.
(chiefly in the plural, dated, Britain) Fingerprint.
(dance) A hip hop dance move in which the dancer simultaneously drops the head while raising an arm, briefly resting their face in the elbow, as if sneezing into their elbow.

verbs.description: dab (third-person singular simple present dabs, present participle dabbing, simple past and past participle dabbed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To press lightly in a repetitive motion with a soft object without rubbing.
examples: I dabbed my face with a towel.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To apply a substance in this way.
examples: He dabbed moisturizing liquid on his face.

entries.meaning: To strike by a thrust; to hit with a sudden blow or thrust.
examples: to dabbe him in the necke

entries.meaning: (slang) To apply hash oil to a heated surface for the purpose of efficient combustion.
(dance, intransitive) To perform the dab dance move, by moving both arms to one side of the body parallel with your head.
examples: Look, my brothas don't dab, we just vossi bop

entries.meaning: One skilful or proficient; an expert; an adept.

description: Late Middle English dabbe, of unknown origin; perhaps related to sense 1 (“to press against lightly”) as in "a soft mass dabbed down."

entries.meaning: A small flatfish of the family Pleuronectidae, especially Limanda limanda; a flounder.
(US) A sand dab, a small flatfish of genus Citharichthys.

adjectives.description: dab (comparative more dab, superlative most dab)
